post_text:
We are so excited to see everyone tomorrow morning! Just a brief reminder of a few changes from last year to help with social distancing.

* We are using three separate entryways and the doors will open at 7:50 AM to allow more time. Classes will still start at 8:10 AM so you have 20 minutes not 10 minutes for drop-off.

* 1st, 2nd, 3rd Grades - Use the playground entry door
* Kinder, 7th, 8th Grades - Main Entrance
* 4th, 5th, 6th Grades - Use walkway near the dumpster
* All students report directly to their classroom, not the gym

* Latch-key students can arrive starting at 6:45 AM and report directly to the gym.

* Pre-K students drop-off starting at 7:35 AM to avoid the rush and allow more social distancing

* Dismissal - This year dismissal will not be lined-up outside but we will send students out when parents arrive. We will start dismissal at 3:00 PM, but our school day won't end until 3:15. We are allowing early dismissal again to allow more time to socially distance. Rather than doing it in 15 minutes, we will have 30 minutes to exit the building.

post_text:
Wow! It was so nice to see everyone and to show off the hard work and effort that went into preparing for the upcoming school year. We all know that it won't be free of challenges, and we appreciate your patience and understanding as we learn together. We are literally building the plane as we are flying, but we will have an in-flight beverage service!

We have a few families that were not able to pick-up their Distance Learning packets on Wednesday or Thursday. We are not at the school today, but you would be able to pick them up from the office starting at 6:30 Tuesday Morning. Your students would be able to access the learning remotely even if they don't have their books, but they won't be able to complete the assignments.

Looking forward to an amazing YEAR and I know that our staff and students are more than up to the challenge.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y7XW-mewUm8

post_text: K-8 Physical Education Teacher Position Description Position: K-8 Physical Education Teacher Reports to: Administrator, Aaron Warren Responsibilities of the Position: 1. Teach Physical Education classes to Kindergarten ‚Äì 8th grade students on a rotational basis. The position also requires overseeing our Spanish program and helping students navigate Rosetta Stone. This is a position which requires a teacher who is positive, high energy, likes to be moving and wants students to find the love of being active. The PE teachers are expected to positively interact with parents, other teachers and school administrators and also are expected to hold themselves up to social standards. Requirements for the Position: Applicants will hold a Bachelor‚Äôs Degree and a teaching certificate valid in the State of Michigan. Background checks will be performed. Pay/Other: Benefits package includes the following: health insurance, 401K, short and long term disability coverage, dental and vision insurance, life insurance coverage, yearly classroom stipend for supplies

post_text:
Everybody please welcome Mrs. Raymond as the new Kindergarten teacher!

Hi! My name is Ida Raymond and I am so excited for the privilege to be the new Kindergarten teacher at Island City Academy. My family and I have been a part of ICA since 2014 when my son began Pre-K. I worked as a lunch aide, after school latchkey helper and a substitute teacher for ICA for about two years. I also have served as a member of the PTO for about 4 years. I am a graduate of Michigan State University (Go Green!) and recently, I earned my teaching certificate. I spent last year teaching English and Creative Writing in Jackson, MI. My husband and I have two children, Benjamin (5th grade) and Adeline (4th grade). We also have a silly chocolate lab named Toby, two cats and most recently 18 chickens. They all keep me very busy! We love to spend our summers camping. When we are home, my children and I love to bake, read books and watch movies.

As Mr. Warren shared in the zoom meetings he attended a Barry-Eaton Health Department (BEHD) meeting, and he was going to share the information when it became available. That information was released on Friday on the BEHD website.

This PDF answers many questions that parents asked in our meeting and includes procedures for exposure by staff and/or students. It also includes information for parents on a screener before you send your child to school. That information starts on page 19 and pages 29 - 42 are for the school to print and post around the building.
https://www.barryeatonhealth.org/sites/default/files/COVID-19%20Return%20to%20School%20Toolkit_BEDHD%20Includes%20APPENDICES%207-31-20.pdf

The link for the Presentation Mr. Warren attended can be found on the BEHD website, but there are changes so the PDF is the most accurate source. Any questions or concerns please call the school or e-mail Mr. Warren at wawarren@islandcity.org

As you are all well aware part of our return to school plan is that all students must wear a "mask" or "face covering" at some point in the day. Please share with your friends and family that live in other areas also as they are donating them to all schools! They can choose their local school and help them also.

post_text:
We are super excited to share that we just ordered additional Chromebooks!

We have always shared them in the K - 3rd grade classrooms. With Covid-19 we really wanted to be able to offer 1:1 devices for all grades. So, as we start our 25th year we will officially be 1:1 with devices for all of our students. Also this year, we are allowing them to be taken home as needed for distance learning.

The only downside is due to the limited production they may not be here till the 2nd week of school but I know our ICA students will be patient!

The meeting schedule is as follows:

- Sunday, July 19 - 3 pm
- Tuesday, July 21 - 9 am
- Tuesday, July 21 - 7 pm

You can find the link to the zoom meetings on the front page of our website: www.islandcity.org

post_text: We have a few limited openings in our Island City Academy Child Care Center for the Fall. The Island City Academy Pre-K is a half-day program that meets from 8:10 ‚Äì 11:20 Monday ‚Äì Friday and follows the Island City Academy school schedule. The program is open to students who are 4 on September 8th and will be eligible for Kindergarten in the fall of 2021. The Pre-K program is tuition-based and the cost is $230 a month, or $2,070 for the year. We are excited to offer a 10% discount for all essential workers. If you are interested in enrolling for the Fall please contact the school at 517-663-0111 for the application packet.

Eaton Rapids High School
May 21 at 7:22 PM ¬∑

Senior Social Studies Student of the Year - Tyler Sutherlin

Tyler is a student who has a student who has excelled in his social studies course. Tyler is very well spoken and has always done well in discussion and arguing his points in class. Tyler is someone who has excelled on the stage, through his roles in the school plays and musicals. He may not have taken all the courses that we offer, but he is someone who has done something unique for Eaton Rapids High School. Tyler was selected as a state representative to the National Youth in Government conference in Washington D.C. He even spoke at the Eaton Rapids Education Foundation Dinner to share his accomplishments. Congratulations Tyler!

Did you know that today was School Principals' Day??
NO??? Me either until I got this most amazing heartfelt message from my students!

Words cannot describe how thankful I am to my students for such a heartfelt message! I miss all of you and cannot wait to see you all again!

To my Students - Thank you all for taking the time to say hi and I miss you all greatly! Keep working hard, eat your veggies, brush your teeth, and always wash behind your ears! Oh...and listen to Mom/Dad and be patient, as they are trying to help with homework. You may need to HELP THEM with your Math homework it's been a while for them! ü§£

#BestJobEver #MyStudentsRock

Thank-you ICA PTO for creating the video....you Ladies ROCK!

Today's Senior Spring Athlete spotlight is our 10 CAAC Senior Scholar Athletes!

Eaton Rapids High School is pleased to announce these 10 outstanding student/athletes as Capital Area Activities Conference Senior Scholar Athletes for the 2019-2020 school year.

Each academic year the Capital Area Activities Conference (CAAC) honors ten seniors from each of the 24 member schools. Unfortunately, due to the current pandemic, the formal ceremony was canceled. However, the CAAC still wants to extend their congratulations to these deserving seniors with a special thanks to Sparrow Health Systems for their continued sponsorship of this event. The Michigan Department of Health and Human Services recently announced a new program: Pandemic EBT.

The Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer Program (P-EBT) program provides temporary funding to address emergency food needs for families affected by the COVID-19 pandemic.

P-EBT food assistance benefits will go to Michigan families with students ages 5-18 that are eligible for free or reduced-price school meals. This includes families currently receiving Food Assistance Program benefits, as well as those not currently enrolled in the program. No application is necessary for eligible families to receive P-EBT benefits.

https://www.michigan.gov/coronavirus/0,9753,7-406-98158-525248--,00.html

post_text:
Students will have the opportunity to virtually meet Michigan State University scientists from The Sci-Files next week and talk to them about their research.

The Sci-Files is an award-winning, specialty show on Impact 89 FM (the MSU Student Radio station) where two MSU graduate students (Daniel Puentes and Chelsie Boodoo) interview MSU students on their research.

We welcome parents and children to join us for a virtual Q&A session on 4/2/2020 at 11 am EST with our interviewees from The Sci-Files! This event is for everyone of all ages; students in Michigan are encouraged to attend with their parents.
Some topics will be astronomy, inflammation, underwater robotics, bone health of racing horses, climate change, data science, and bacterial infections. Episodes can be found on your favorite podcast directory or scifiles.org and new episodes air Sundays at 9:30 am.

People can rsvp at https://forms.gle/UQHUo8kUKQLnqBwW9

To all of our ICA Families,

I am sure that by now you‚Äôve seen this article related to the memo sent out from MDE. This decision from MDE does not in any way impact what we are doing here at ICA. As I mentioned last week we are only tracking the hours spent in case they do allow us to use the time. Our decision to transition to distance learning was done for the benefit of our students, and not to meet any specific time requirements. So, long story short, the announcement today does not change what we are doing here at ICA. Please continue to encourage your students to keep working hard and use the resources we have available online.

Have a great weekend and we will get back to it again next week! Remember, even if it‚Äôs from home, we still only have 4 days next week! Spring Break starts next Thursday at 3:15!

Mr. Warren

post_text:
Good Evening,

As you know the Governor is officially closing all schools starting Monday morning. We will be working with the students tomorrow to determine needs to ensure they have access to the curriculum for the next 3 weeks.

Our School Board had already been taking pro-active steps to prepare since our February Board meeting. We had hope to avoid the outcome but we will implement our plan.

More information will be coming tomorrow with your students.

Mr. Warren

text: REMINDER: Today is an Early Release Day at ICA. Students will be dismissed at 1:30 pm. Have a great Thanksgiving Break!

post_text:
Good Evening,

As we start our Thanksgiving week we wanted to remind everyone of the schedule this week. We will have our Board Sponsored Thanksgiving Luncheon on Tuesday including our Pre K students. The lunch is a turkey luncheon catered and served by our School Board. Students will be released after lunch at 1:30 that afternoon, we are closed Wednesday through Friday for the holiday.

Parents also just a reminder of our 24-hour policy when it comes to vomiting and fevers. If your child is vomiting or has a fever please ensure they are free of both for at least 24 hours before returning to school. This will hopefully help us prevent the passing of the sickness around the classrooms. We have had a lot of recurring illnesses this year and we want to try and prevent it as we move into the winter. Also, please help remind your child to wash their hands with soap and water often, but especially after using the restroom.

Have a great evening and Happy Thanksgiving Week!

post_text: Come check out the Pumpkin Walk from 6:30 - 8:30 tonight!
shared_text:
Island City Pumpkin Walk
October 27, 2019 at 12:52 PM ¬∑

It's a beautiful day for a pumpkin walk! Come out tonight from 6:30-8:30 to see these pumpkins all lit up. You'll be glad you did!

We are on South Clinton Trail, next to the Hamlin TWP Fire Dept. $5 donation per family to walk the trail appreciated, not required. Hot dogs, chili, doughnuts, hot cider, hot cocoa available for $1 each.

post_text:
Do you think you can beat these pumpkins!?

Remember, our class competition for pumpkin carving are due Friday morning. Place pumpkins by class square. No painted pumpkins, nothing inside pumpkins. Judging will be based on the quantity of creative & quality carved pumpkins.

The challenge is on!

post_text: We are having a Pumpkin Carving Event this evening from 3:30 - 6 pm. Come carve some pumpkins that will be displayed along our Pumpkin Walk the Friday and Saturday. We will be located at the Pavilion at Hamlin Park. We have a few carving utensils but bring your own if you have them!
